# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: amsterdam-airport-schiphol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The **A4 motorway**, also called **Rijksweg 4**, is a motorway in the Netherlands running southwards from Amsterdam to the Belgian border near Zandvliet, north of the city of Antwerp.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The 119-kilometre-long (74 mi) A4 is divided into two sections; the first and longer section runs from Amsterdam to the A15 near the city of Rotterdam, while the second section starts near Heijningen, where the A29 and the A4 meet, going to the Belgian border.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Between the A29 near the village of Klaaswaal (south of Rotterdam), and the Sabina interchange (where the A4-A29 meets the A59), the route is numbered A29.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Three European routes run concurrently with this highway at some point: E19, E30, and E312.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] There are no authorized plans for the missing link between Pernis (south of Schiedam and west of Rotterdam) and the A29 near Klaaswaal, though right-of-way has been acquired for the future A29 interchange with the A4.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The A4 begins in the province of North Holland in the southeastern part of the city of Amsterdam at an interchange on the A10 ring road called Knooppunt De Nieuwe Meer.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] At this interchange, the E19 continues from the eastern segment of the A10 onto the A4, and the E22 begins northwards along the A10.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Even though the A4 starts at this interchange, the A4 has priority from the eastern direction toward the interchange, as entering onto the A4 from the east does not require a turn (in contrast to staying on the A10, which requires a turn to the right).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] From the north, staying on the A10 and entering the A4 both require a turn.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] From the Knooppunt De Nieuwe Meer interchange, the road travels to the southeast, concurrent with a rail line that runs between both directions of the motorway.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] After 4 kilometres (2.5 mi), the road intersects A9 at the Badhoevedorp partial cloverleaf interchange.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] After leaving this interchange, the rails travel southwards underground towards Amsterdam Airport Schiphol.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Continuing towards Schiphol, the A4 enters the 650-meter-long (2,130 ft) Schiphol tunnel underneath a runway and two taxiways.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Exit 2 of the motorway serves the airport.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] After this, another taxiway bridge crosses the A4.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Southeast of Schiphol, A5 joins the A4 at the De Hoek incomplete interchange.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] This interchange lacks a ramp from the A5 to the northbound lane of the A4, because the A9 already serves traffic from A5 to A4 in both directions.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Shortly before leaving the province of North Holland and entering South Holland, the A44 branches off of the A4 at the Burgerveen interchange.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] This interchange is also incomplete, as one can only travel onto the A44 from Amsterdam.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The road crosses the Ringvaart using the Ringvaart aqueduct and enters South Holland.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] At the border between Leiderdorp and Leiden, the road uses the Limes aqueduct to travel under the Oude Rijn river.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In the Vinex-location Leidschenveen-Ypenburg in the municipality of The Hague, the motorway connects to the Prins Clausplein stack interchange with the A12 and the E30, and the Ypenburg interchange with the E30 (A13) and the E19.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In between these two interchanges, the A4, the E19, and the E30 all run concurrently, and at this location, there is a basketweave exchange.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The outer lanes of the basketweave are for connecting the A13 and the stack exchange ramps to and from the A12, and the inner lanes are the continuing the A4.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Leaving the basketweave interchange, the A4, now concurrent with the E30, continues southwards towards southeastern Delft, where it continues partially below ground level through the Midden-Delfland region.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] It then enters the Rotterdam region at the semi-directional Kethelplein T-interchange, where the A4 travels to the south and the A20 (concurrent with the E25) travels from east to west.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] When traveling under train tracks, the road approaches exit 16, which allows access to Vlaardingen to the east and Schiedam to the west.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] This exit is special, as the northern exit and southern entrance first travel parallel with the A4 through the Beneluxtunnel under the Nieuwe Maas river.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] This results in more lanes for drivers to use, since the ramps connect to the A4 on the southern side of the Nieuwe Maas.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] They branch off shortly after and enter the Benelux interchange (named 17a so as to not confuse drivers, since the previous exit on A15 to the west is already exit 17), an incomplete T-interchange with only a southbound exit and a northbound entrance.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] This interchange is the southern terminus of this segment of the A4, and the road continues both west and east as the A15.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The final segment of the A4 with the A29 starts in the province of North Brabant near Heijningen at the Hellegatsplein interchange, crossing the estuaries Hollands Diep (to the east), Haringvliet, and the Volkerak (to the west).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Shortly after, the A4 enters the Sabina trumpet interchange (named after a nearby fort) with the A59.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The A29 and the A59 both enter this interchange from the north, and the A29 ends here.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The A4 continues to the south, while the A59 branches off to the east.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Crossing the Dintel and passing by Dinteloord, the A4 makes a large curve to the west and subsequently continues to the south, forming a tangent around Steenbergen.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In the southern part of the curve, the A4 travels along Fort Henricus, a now-demolished fort with only the shape of the land intact.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Here, the road also tunnels under the Steenbergse Haven using the third Steenbergen aan Zee aqueduct.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The A4 continues southbound and passes Bergen op Zoom to the east, with a few exits serving this city.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Between exits 27 and 28, the A58 runs concurrent with the E312, which joins A4 to the south.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] All three roads travel concurrently southbound, and at the Markiezaat trumpet interchange, the A58 and the E312 both leave the A4 and travel to the west, entering the province of Zeeland.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The A4, however, continues to the south until reaching the Belgian border near Zandvliet.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] A few meters before crossing the border, the northbound entrance and southbound exit ramps start on Dutch soil; the rest of this exit is within Belgium and is part of the Belgian A12.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Work started on A4 in the 1930s, and followed high construction standards for the time.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] By the late 1930s, various sections were in service.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] One of these roads went between Amsterdam and Sassenheim, and while part of the historical A4, it is not on the current route.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 1938, ground was broken for Rijksweg 4A, which went between Burgerveen and Leidschendam.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] This road would later be renumbered to Rijksweg 4, and it now forms a section of A4.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Groundwork began in 1939 near Leidschendam, but was cancelled in 1942 due to World War II.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Construction of the Ypenburg interchange also started that same year.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 1957, the A4 opened between the Ypenburg and Leidschendam interchanges, the latter now known as Prins Clausplein, with 2 lanes in both directions.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Construction from the latter interchange further north to Hoogmade was done in 1958.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 1960 and 1961, the section between the Burgerveen and Hoogmade interchanges opened, including an aqueduct underneath the Ringvaart canal.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] One lane of Rijksweg 4 between Klaaswaal and the Hellegatsplein interchange opened in 1964, and in 1965, another lane was added.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] This section is currently designated as the A29.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 1966, another standalone section of the A4 was opened with 3 lanes in each direction, between Amsterdam (where the Badhoevedorp interchange is now located) and Hoofddorp, leaving a gap between Hoofddorp and the Burgerveen interchange.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The Badhoevedorp interchange, which is between Amsterdam and Hoofddorp, was opened a year later in 1967, which was the first cloverleaf interchange with collector/distributor lanes in the Netherlands.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 1972, this segment of the A4 was lengthened northward to connect to the De Nieuwe Meer interchange.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Another unconnected section of the A4 was constructed at the Kethelplein en Pernis interchange in 1967 in western Rotterdam.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] This included the construction of the Beneluxtunnel under the Nieuwe Maas, which was a tolled tunnel at construction but was converted to free in 1980.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 1972, this section was extended southward to the Benelux interchange.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 1971, the sections of Rijksweg 4 designated as A29 were extended from the Hellegatsplein interchange to Dinteloord.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] It was first administratively and publicly known as Rijksweg 19, but in 1976, it was renumbered to Rijksweg 4 and designated as A29.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Another section of Rijksweg 4 concurrent with A58 was opened around Bergen op Zoom between 1973 and 1976.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 1985, the Leidschendam interchange was renamed and redesigned to a 4-level stack interchange Prins Clausplein.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The segment between Badhoevedorp and Hoofddorp was widened to 2x4 lanes in 1988, and ten years later in 1998, the tubes in the Schipholtunnel were renewed.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 1993, the section around Bergen op Zoom was extended southwards from the Markiezaat interchange (where concurrency with A58 stopped) to the Belgian border near Zandvliet, where it connected to the Belgian A12.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 1999, the section between The Hague-Zuid and Delft-Zuid opened for traffic after the section between the Ypenburg interchange and The Hague-Zuid was opened with 3 lanes in each direction in 1998.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 1998, the A4 between Zoeterwoude and Leidschendam was widened to 2x3 lanes, and in 1999, the part between Leidschendam and the Prins Clausplein interchange was widened to 2x5 lanes.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 2003, a new set of express lanes was added to both directions between Hoofddorp and the Burgerveen interchange, giving this segment a total of 2x5 lanes.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Formerly restricted to rush hours, these express lanes were permanently opened on 2 April 2013.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 2006, the segment between Hoogmade and Roelafarendsveen was widened to 2x3 lanes.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 1997, construction had started on the second Beneluxtunnel in Rotterdam.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] On 11 May 2002, the project was completed with 4x2 lanes and a reversible lane, allowing for 5 available lanes in the peak direction.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Between the De Nieuwe Meer and Badhoevedorp interchanges in southwestern Amsterdam, express lanes were added in 2011 to relieve the 2x3 lanes on this segment of the A4 during rush hours, which saw use by 180,000 vehicles every day.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Construction for the express lanes was started in the summer of 2010.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The same year, construction also started on new lanes between Hoofddorp and Hoofddorp-Zuid for the construction of the realigned N201, commissioned by the province of North Holland.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] These parallel lanes are between the Den Ruygen Hoek rest area and Schiphol exit.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Entering the Burgerveen interchange from the north, the A4 has 2x5 lanes, which is reduced to 2x2 after leaving the interchange.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Even though a lot of traffic is headed to the A44 at this interchange, this was still an important bottleneck, with some 100,000 vehicles every day in the Ringvaart aqueduct that also lacked emergency lanes.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Further south, the bridge over the Oude Rijn river was another bottleneck with only 2x2 lanes.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] After this segment, 2x3 lanes were once again available.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The A4 towards Amsterdam was widened to three lanes between Hoogmade and Roelfarendsveen in 2005, with a lane added to the other direction the following year.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The low bridge over the Oude Rijn was replaced by the Limes aqueduct, making the A4 deeper than 1,400 metres (4,600 ft).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] A second Ringvaart aqueduct was also constructed near Roelfarendsveen, which was formally opened on 31 July 2010, after which the existing aqueduct from 1961 was renovated.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] On 24 November 2010, the 2x3 lanes were formally opened by minister Melanie Schultz, significantly reducing traffic congestion as a result.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The opening of the Limes aqueduct was in two phases.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The first aqueduct was opened in 2012 next to the existing A4, almost immediately with 2x3 narrowed lanes, after which the old A4 was destroyed and the construction of the second aqueduct was started.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] On 25 October 2014, the second aqueduct opened.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The aqueduct has space for 2x5 lanes, plus emergency lanes.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The aqueduct was completely widened on 1 December 2014, when the aqueduct toward The Hague gained three normal-width lanes.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Until 2015, the A4 southwest of Delft had its southern terminus of the section start in Amsterdam, with another section starting at the Kethelplein interchange in Schiedam and running southwards.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The missing segment caused huge congestion on the adjacent parallel A13, which was the only motorway connecting The Hague and Rotterdam.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] There have been plans for creating this missing link in the past, but the government diverted finances to other projects twice.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 2006, it was estimated that this 7-kilometre-long (4.3 mi) missing section would cost €700 million to build, and in 2009, the Dutch government decided that this section would be constructed.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] On 2 September 2010, minister Camiel Eurlings made a record of the decision for this road segment, and on 6 July 2011, all appeals against the decision were dismissed.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The missing link was completed in late 2015 and was opened on 18 December 2015 (northbound) and 20 December 2015 (southbound).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The section between Dinteloord and Halsteren until 2015 is the latest missing link of the A4 to have been constructed.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] It connects the south end of the A29 with another segment of the A4 that was already constructed near Bergen op Zoom.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Finances for the 16-kilometre-long (9.9 mi) missing link were first acquired in 2005, consisting of a budget of €218 million.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] In 2006, contracts for construction near Halsteren were awarded to construction companies, and in 2007, the government decided that the A4 would be constructed west of Steenbergen, which would require creating an aqueduct under the Steenbergsche Haven canal.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] While a road east of Steenbergen would be much shorter and less expensive, it would have traversed through the Mark river area, which was opposed by many since it is seen as an important natural aspect in the region.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The first segment of the missing link, the so-called Halsteren bypass, was opened on 21 December 2007 by Minister of Transport Camiel Eurlings.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] This bypass consists of a 4-kilometer-long (2.5 mi) northwards extension from the existing southern section of A4 from exit 27 to provincial road N286 north of Halsteren, to relieve provincial road N259 through that same town.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] By the end of 2010, construction had begun, and it was planned that the road would have been finished by the end of 2013.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] On 14 March 2012, the new segment of highway around Steenbergen was officially approved by the Dutch Council of State.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] On 18 June 2012, another small extension was added to the southern segment of the A4, a 1.5-kilometer-long (0.93 mi) highway linking Halsteren and Klutsdorp.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] By the end of December 2013, the final segment around Steenbergen between Klutsdorp and A29 near Dinteloord was completed, which created a continuously running link between Rotterdam and the Belgian border over A29 and A4.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Due to the rearrangement of the A9 near Badhoevedorp, the Badhoevedorp interchange with the A4 will also be altered.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The new arrangement is intended to make the A9 travel around Badhoevedorp in the shape of an arc, necessitating the rearrangement of the interchange.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Construction has been started in December 2013 and is planned to be done in 2017.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Because of the construction of the Rijnlandroute, which will be designated as the N434, the parallel structure near Zoeterwoude will have to be lengthened even further southward up to the Hofvliet interchange with the Rijnlandroute.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] On 9 May 2014, the draft of a plan to widen part of the A4 was made available for inspection, followed by the real planning procedure on 17 December 2014.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Construction on this will according to the plan be started in 2015.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The A4 will be widened to 2x4 lanes between the new interchange Hofvliet and exit Leidschendam.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] To allow this, only a southern lane needs to be built because there is already a northbound emergency lane present.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] On 26 September 2013, the decision to start was made, and on 11 July 2014, the draft planning procedure was shown, followed by the final planning procedure on 18 December 2014.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Construction is planned for completion around 2020.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] There are plans to allow more capacity between Leidschendam and The Hague-Zuid due to the traffic congestion between the Ypenburg and Prins Clausplein interchanges, because of the development of the Rotterdam and The Hague regions.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] There are also plans for the A4 to make The Hague less reliant on the Utrechtsebaan.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] On 15 May 2012, the draft *rijksstructuurvisie* was determined, and on 21 November 2012, the final *rijksstructuurvisie* followed.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The plans are to change this part of the A4 between 2020 and 2023.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] At this point in time, there is no motorway between interchange Benelux and the A29 near Klaaswaal.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] However, an extension of the A4 southwards is possible without changing the layout of the Benelux interchange.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] This missing section was already approved by the government in 1961, as part of the then-called Road 19, and space was reserved by the government in 2005.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] By constructing this missing link, the A4 would be one continuously running road from the Kethelplein interchange, west of the city of Rotterdam, to the Belgian border.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] It would also relieve the A15 and A29 from traffic jams, since they currently serve as a link between the two sections of the A4.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Supporters of the planned 12-kilometer-long motorway state that cities like Hoogvliet, Spijkenisse, Barendrecht and Rotterdam would be significantly less congested, and that overall traffic flow would be restored.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Opponents, among which are environmentalists, state that the construction of the missing link would only result in more traffic and thus more congestion, leading to negative environmental effects.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] Since the A15 and the A29 are currently being widened, this section of the A4 seems more and more unlikely to be built.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] The motorway section between Klaaswaal and the Sabina interchange near Dinteloord is currently known and designated as the A29, but the intention is to include it in the A4 motorway and designate it as such in the future.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] When the missing link between interchange Benelux and Klaaswaal is completed, this section will be renumbered to the A4, in order to create a continuously numbered motorway between the Kethelplein interchange and the Belgian border.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a4-motorway-netherlands] For now, however, this section of road is still being numbered as the A29 to avoid confusion.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] The **A5 motorway** is a motorway in the Netherlands.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] With a length of 17 kilometres (11 mi), it is one of the shortest motorways in the country.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] The A5 serves as a western by-pass for the city of Amsterdam, relieving the western part of the A10 motorway from through traffic towards Zaanstad and the northern part of the province.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] It also forms a shortcut between the A4 motorway and A9 motorway, reducing travel time and distance between The Hague and Haarlem and Alkmaar.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] This shortcut relieved the busy intersection Badhoevedorp.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] The current A5 was opened in two sections: the first on November 8, 2003 connecting the A4 with the A9 resulting in two new interchanges: interchange De Hoek (A4/A5) and interchange Raasdorp (A5/A9).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] This section of A5 has no exits, although there is an exit ramp towards Hoofddorp when heading south.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] Because this junction is located just before interchange De Hoek, it is considered to be part of the A4 and therefore has no exit number.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] The only object one comes across when driving on this part of the A5, is a short tunnel (the Rolbaantunnel) underneath the section connecting Schiphol Airport's *Polderbaan* runway (the most western runway of Schiphol) to the rest of the airport.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] Directly parallel to the A5 motorway, on its east, is another runway, the *Zwanenburgbaan*.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] The second section of the A5 continues from interchange Raasdorp towards the western seaports of Amsterdam ("Westelijk Havengebied") and finally connects with the A10 just south of the Coentunnel.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] This interchange is part of the interchange Coenplein, which originally only connected the A10 with the A8 motorway at the north side of the tunnel.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] Now the interchange is in fact a double interchange with the tunnel in between.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] This section of the A5 opened in two stages.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] First, in December 2012 the section between interchange Raasdorp and the IJmuiden junction opened.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] In May 2013 the remaining part including the connection with the A10 opened.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] This part also includes one of the longest motorway viaducts of the Netherlands, giving motorists a panorama of the seaports.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] In the future, a new part of Amsterdam might be built.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] This "Parkwijk" can be connected with the A5 by building a new junction between interchange Raasdorp en junction 2.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] Exit number 1 has been reserved for this possible new junction.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] Between interchange De Hoek and interchange Raasdorp the speed limit on the A5 is 130 km/h (81 mph).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] Between interchange Raasdorp and interchange Coenplein the speed limit is 100 km/h (62 mph).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a5-motorway-netherlands] The entire route is in North Holland Province.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] The **A9 motorway** is a motorway in the Netherlands.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] The motorway starts off by going from the A1 at Diemen (junction Diemen) to the A2 at junction 'Holendrecht' (on the 'Gaasperdammerweg').
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] Here one drives approximately two kilometers south by means of the combined A9/A2 before the A9 heads off to the west again towards Amstelveen, junction 'Badhoevedorp' (A4), junction 'Raasdorp' (A5), junction 'Rottepolderplein' (A200) and on to junction 'Velsen' (A22).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] Hereafter, the A9 goes further northward by means of the Wijkertunnel under the North Sea Canal, junction 'Beverwijk' (A22) to Alkmaar.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] At this point, the A9 motorway becomes the N9 highway and proceeds until De Kooy (at Den Helder).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] In 1996, the Wijkertunnel was opened and integrated into the A9.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] The original route of the A9 ran through the Velsertunnel where there is also a connection with the A208.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] This part still exists but this portion of motorway has been re-numbered to A22.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] The part between A1 and A2 is four lanes; between A2 and Rottepolderplein it is six lanes.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] Hereafter the way is mainly four lanes, with short pieces in the area of the Wijkertunnel that are six lanes.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] With regard to the Gaasperdammerweg, it is noted in the original plans that this road would not become a motorway.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] The plan was to build a local link-road for the occupants of the Bijlmermeer.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] The section between A2/A9 and A1/A6 was never built, although this would have formed a natural connection between A9 and A6.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] Because of this, the Gaasperdammerweg has developed into an overflowing connection between A2 and A1.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] Discussions on extending the A9 in a straight line to the A6 are still going on.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/a9-motorway-netherlands] Because this part of the route would pass by the Naardermeer, environmentalists oppose this plan.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/aalborg-airport] Aalborg Airport was opened in 1938 as the second national airport.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/aalborg-airport] During World War II, Aalborg was occupied and used by the German Air Force.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/aalborg-airport] The 3rd and 5th squadrons of *Bordfliegergruppe 196* (Embarked Air Group 196) as well as the group's staff unit, used Aalborg as a base for maritime reconnaissance flights and detachments serving aboard German Navy surface combatants.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/aalborg-airport] The present terminal building is from 2001.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/aalborg-airport] The airport was enlarged during 2007 and 2013, increasing the terminal size and number of gates.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/aalborg-airport] Scandinavian Airlines flew nonstop to Newark International Airport between April and October 2023.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/aalborg-airport] However, SAS discontinued the route after the first season due to low passenger numbers.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/aalborg-airport] Ryanair previously operated flights to London Stansted and seasonal flights to Girona, but they discontinued operations from the airport in March 2025 due to a new aviation tax levied by the Danish government..
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/aalborg-airport] Ryanair still operates from Aarhus Airport, roughly 100 km to the South .
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/aalborg-airport] The airport is at an elevation of 10 feet (3 m) above mean sea level.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/aalborg-airport] North Flying has its head office in the North Flying Terminal at Aalborg Airport.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/aalborg-airport] Greenland Express had its headquarters at the airport as well.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/aalborg-airport] The airport is served by Aalborg Airport railway station on the Aalborg Airport railway line.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/aalborg-airport] The trains go to Copenhagen Central Station, calling at three stops in Aalborg and then several cities along the route.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/aalborg-airport] The station started operation on 13 December 2020.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax was one of the most successful clubs in the world in the 20th century.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] According to the International Federation of Football History & Statistics, Ajax was the seventh-most successful European club of the 20th century and *The World's Club Team of the Year* in 1992.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] According to German magazine *Kicker*, Ajax was the second-most successful European club of the 20th century.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The club is one of five teams that have earned the right to keep the European Cup and to wear a multiple-winner badge.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 1972, they completed the continental treble by winning the Eredivisie, KNVB Cup, and the European Cup.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] They also won the first (albeit unofficial) European Super Cup against Rangers in January 1973.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax's most recent international trophies are the 1995 Intercontinental Cup, 1995 UEFA Super Cup and the 1995 Champions League, where they defeated Milan in the final; they lost the 1996 Champions League final on penalties to Juventus.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 1995, Ajax was crowned as *World Team of the Year* by *World Soccer* magazine.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax is also one of four teams to win the continental treble and the Intercontinental Cup or Club World Cup in the same season/calendar year; this was achieved in the 1971–72 season.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax is one of five clubs to have won all three major UEFA club competitions played until 2021.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] They have also won the Intercontinental Cup twice, the 1991–92 UEFA Cup, as well as the Karl Rappan Cup, a predecessor of the UEFA Intertoto Cup in 1962.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax plays at the Johan Cruyff Arena, which opened as the Amsterdam ArenA in 1996 and was renamed in 2018.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] They previously played at De Meer Stadion and the Amsterdam Olympic Stadium (for international matches).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Throughout their history, Ajax have cultivated a reputation for scouting, spotting and developing young talent, and have remained focused on developing a youth system.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax was founded in Amsterdam on 18 March 1900.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The club achieved promotion to the highest level of Dutch football in 1911 and had its first major success in 1917, winning the KNVB Beker, the Netherlands' national cup.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The following season, Ajax became national champion for the first time.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The club defended its title in 1918–19, becoming the only team to achieve an unbeaten season in the Netherlands Football League Championship.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Throughout the 1920s, Ajax was a strong regional power, winning the Eerste Klasse West division in 1921, 1927 and 1928, but could not maintain its success at the national level.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] This changed in the 1930s, with the club winning five national championships (1931, 1932, 1934, 1937, 1939), making it the most successful Dutch team of the decade.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax won its second KNVB Cup in 1942–43, and an eighth Dutch title in 1946–47, the last season the club was managed by Englishman Jack Reynolds, who, up to this point, had overseen all of its national championship successes as well as its 1917 KNVB Cup win.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 1956, the first season of the Netherlands' new professional league, the Eredivisie, was played with Ajax participating as a founding member.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The Amsterdam club became the first national champions under the new format and made its debut in the European Champion Clubs' Cup the following year, losing to Hungarian champions Vasas SC 6–2 on aggregate at the quarter-final stage.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The team was again Eredivisie champions in 1960 and won a third KNVB Cup in 1961.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 1965, Rinus Michels, who had played for the club between 1946 and 1958, was appointed manager of Ajax, implementing his philosophy of Total Football which was to become synonymous with both Ajax and the Netherlands national team.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] A year earlier, Johan Cruyff, who would go on to become widely regarded as the greatest Dutch footballer of all time, made his debut.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Between them, Michels and Cruyff led Ajax through the most successful period in its history, winning seven Eredivisie titles, four KNVB Cups and three European Cups.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax won the Dutch championship in 1966, 1967 and 1968, and reached the 1969 European Cup final, losing to Milan.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] During the 1966–67 season, Ajax scored a record 122 goals in an Eredivisie season and also won the KNVB Cup to achieve its first league and cup double.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 1969–70, Ajax won a fourth Dutch league championship and second league and cup double in five seasons, winning 27 out of 34 league matches and scoring 100 goals.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The 1970–71 season saw Ajax retain the KNVB Cup and reach the 1971 European Cup final, where they defeated Panathinaikos 2–0 with goals from Dick van Dijk and Arie Haan to become continental champions for the first time, with Cruyff being named European Footballer of the Year.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] After this success, Michels departed to become manager of Barcelona and was replaced by the Romanian Ștefan Kovács.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In Kovács' first season, Ajax completed a treble of the European Cup, the Eredivisie and a third consecutive KNVB Cup.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The following season, the team beat Argentine Club Atlético Independiente to win the 1972 Intercontinental Cup and retained their Eredivisie and European Cup titles, becoming the first club to win three consecutive European Cups since Real Madrid in the 1950s.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 1973, Michels' Barcelona broke the world transfer record to bring Cruyff to the Catalan team.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Kovács also departed to become manager of the France national team, signalling the end of this period of international success.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 1976–77, Ajax won its first domestic championship in four seasons and recorded a double of the Eredivisie and KNVB Cup two years later.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The early 1980s saw the return of Cruyff to the club, as well as the emergence of young players Marco van Basten and Frank Rijkaard.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The team won back-to-back Eredivisie titles in 1982 and 1983, with all three playing a significant role in the latter.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] After Cruyff's sale to rivals Feyenoord in 1983, van Basten became Ajax's key player, top scoring in the Eredivisie for four seasons between 1983–84 and 1986–87.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 1985, Cruyff returned to Ajax as manager and the team ended his first season in charge with 120 goals from 34 matches.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] However, Ajax still finished as runner-up to PSV by eight points.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The following season, Ajax again lost out on the Eredivisie title to PSV, but won the European Cup Winners' Cup, its first continental trophy in 14 years.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] After this, Cruyff left the club to become manager of Barcelona and Rijkaard and van Basten were sold to Sporting CP and Milan respectively.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Despite these losses, Ajax reached a second consecutive Cup Winners' Cup final in 1988, where they lost to Belgian club KV Mechelen.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The 1988–89 season saw Dennis Bergkamp, a young forward who had first appeared under Cruyff in 1986, establish himself as a regular goalscorer for Ajax.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Bergkamp helped Ajax to the Eredivisie title and was the top scorer in the division in 1990–91, 1991–92 and 1992–93.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Under the management of Louis van Gaal, Ajax won the UEFA Cup in 1992 to become the second club, after Juventus, to have won all three major European club competitions.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The team regained the Dutch championship in 1993–94, and won it again in 1994–95 and 1995–96 to become the first Ajax side to win three back-to-back championships since 1968.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The height of van Gaal's success came in 1994–95, where Ajax became the first, and to date only, team to complete an entire Eredivisie season unbeaten.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The team also won its first European Cup since its 1970s era, defeating Milan in the 1995 UEFA Champions League final 1–0, with the winning goal scored by 18-year-old Patrick Kluivert.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax again reached the final one year later, and was defeated on penalties by Juventus.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax's return as a European force was short-lived, as van Gaal and several members of the squad soon departed to some of the continent's biggest clubs.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The 2000s was a lean decade for the club, with only two Eredivisie championships won.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] However, Ajax's academy continued to produce star players such as Wesley Sneijder and Rafael van der Vaart.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 2010, Frank de Boer was appointed manager of Ajax and led the club to its first league title in seven years, and record 30th title overall, in the 2010–11 season.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] This was followed by back-to-back wins in 2011–12 and 2012–13 to match his three consecutive titles as a player in the 1990s.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 2013–14, Ajax was again Eredivisie champions, winning four consecutive league titles for the first time in club history.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] After finishing as runner-up to PSV in both 2014–15 and 2015–16, de Boer resigned as Ajax head coach in May 2016.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Peter Bosz took over the club and led them to the 2017 UEFA Europa League final, their first European final in 21 years.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] They lost to Manchester United with a lineup that was the youngest ever in a European final, averaging an age of 22 years and 282 days.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] For the third consecutive season, they finished runner-up in the Eredivisie, this time to Feyenoord.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The 2018–19 season for Ajax involved a remarkable run in the UEFA Champions League.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Due to their runner-up finish in the 2017–18 Eredivisie, Ajax entered the tournament in the second qualifying round.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] After successive victories against Sturm Graz, Standard Liège and Dynamo Kyiv, they qualified for the group stage.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax was drawn in a group with German champions Bayern Munich, Portuguese side Benfica and Greek champions AEK Athens.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax finished runner-up in this group, qualifying for the knockout stages, where it was drawn against three-time defending champions Real Madrid.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] After losing 1–2 in the first leg, they defeated Real Madrid 4–1 in the away match, stunning the defending champions in their own stadium, the Santiago Bernabéu, with an aggregate score of 5–3.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Dušan Tadić was awarded a perfect score of 10 by *L'Équipe* following the match.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Thus, Ajax progressed to the quarter-finals and was drawn with Italian champions Juventus.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In the first leg in the Johan Cruyff Arena, they drew 1–1.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In the second leg at the Juventus Stadium, Ajax came from behind to win 2–1 and 3–2 on aggregate.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Matthijs de Ligt scored the winning goal for Ajax to help the team advance to its first Champions League semi-final since 1997.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] There, they would face English side Tottenham Hotspur.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In the first leg of the semi-final, Ajax beat Tottenham 1–0 away from home.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In the second leg, Ajax scored twice in the first half to generate a 3–0 lead on aggregate.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] However, in the second half, Lucas Moura scored three times, including in the 6th minute of added time, resulting in Ajax losing via the away goals rule.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax was in first place on goal difference when the Eredivisie was declared void, preventing them being Dutch champions for the 35th time, but still qualified for the 2020–21 UEFA Champions League.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In this, it was eliminated again, but in 2021 it reached the quarter-finals of the Europa League.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] That season, it again won both the national title and the KNVB Cup.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In the 2021-22 season, Ajax again became champion of the Netherlands.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] It had to give up the KNVB Cup and the Johan Cruijff Shield to competitor PSV because it came out on the losing end in both finals.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In European terms, Ajax achieved first place in the Champions League group, all six matches were won, mostly by a wide margin.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] After the winter break, Ajax was narrowly eliminated in the eighth finals by the Portuguese Benfica Lisboa (Lisbon) (2–2 away, 0–1 at home).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] As of 1 July 2022, Alfred Schreuder succeeded Erik ten Hag, who left for Manchester United, as Ajax's coach.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Most of the key players from previous seasons left during the summer transfer period, but there was also a lot of reinvestment.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax started the 2022/23 season relatively well with six consecutive victories in the Eredivisie.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] But Ajax was eliminated from the Champions League quite quickly in a group with Liverpool, Napoli and Rangers.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] At home against Napoli on 4 October 2022, they even lost by 5 goals (1–6), Ajax's biggest defeat ever in European competition.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] After seven consecutive matches without a win, head coach Alfred Schreuder was dismissed.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] John Heitinga succeeded Schreuder as interim manager.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Under Heitinga, Ajax failed to turn things around despite a good start, with seven wins in a row.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax finished third in the Eredivisie, behind champions Feyenoord and runners-up PSV.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] This was the club's lowest ranking since the 2008/09 season, in which it also finished third.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] After the winter break, Ajax was eliminated in the first knockout phase of the Europa League by Union Berlin (3–1).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax did reach the final of the KNVB Cup, but lost to PSV on penalties (3–2).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] On 19 May 2023, Sven Mislintat took over as Ajax's sports director.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] He succeeded Marc Overmars, who left in early 2022.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Mislintat appointed Maurice Steijn as head coach.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Mislintat spent approximately 111 million euros on transfers.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax had its worst start to the season in fifty-nine years.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] On 29 October 2023, Ajax reached a historic low.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] This put Ajax in last place, 18th place in the Eredivisie, for the first time since the club was founded.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The position of director Mislintat became an embarrassment after it emerged that he had arranged a transfer through a player agent who was an investor in his company.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In the evening of 24 September, Mislintat was fired with immediate effect; among other things, a lack of broad support within the club was one of the reasons.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] A day after the loss against PSV, it was announced that John van 't Schip would become the head coach until the end of the season.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Under the leadership of Van 't Schip, Ajax managed to climb to fifth place in the Eredivisie.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In the Europa League, Ajax finished third, which meant a place in the next season's Conference League, where it eventually lost to Aston Villa in the round of 16.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In the cup, Ajax was eliminated 3–2 by the third division amateurs of USV Hercules.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In the summer of 2024, a rebuild began, with a new board of directors and Alex Kroes and Marijn Beuker as Technical Director and Director of Football.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] They hired Francesco Farioli as new head coach, the first foreign coach since 1998.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Under his leadership, Ajax reached the league phase of the Europa League, where it finished eleventh.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] On 9 February 2025, Ajax finished the weekend on the first place for the first time since November 2022.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax would end the season second to PSV, despite being nine points clear of their rivals with five matches to go.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Due to the late collapse that cost them the title and escalating tensions over transfers, tactics and finances, Farioli decided to leave Ajax on 19 May 2025.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The club is also particularly famous for its renowned youth programme that has produced many Dutch talents over the years.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax also regularly supplies the Dutch national youth teams with local players.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax has also expanded its talent searching programme to South Africa with Ajax Cape Town.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax Cape Town was set up with the help of Rob Moore.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax has also had a satellite club in the United States under the name Ajax America, until it filed for bankruptcy.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] There are some youth players from Ajax Cape Town that have been drafted into the Eredivisie squad, such as South African internationals Steven Pienaar and Thulani Serero and Cameroonian international Eyong Enoh.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 2011, Ajax opened its first youth academies outside the Netherlands when the club partnered with George Kazianis and All Star Consultancy in Greece to open the Ajax Hellas Youth Academy.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The offices are based in Nea Smyrni, Attica, with the main training facility located on the island of Corfu, hosting a total of 15 football youth academies throughout Greece and Cyprus.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Eddie van Schaik heads the organization as coach and consultant, introducing the Ajax football philosophy at the various football training camps of the country.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 2016, Ajax launched the ACA (Ajax Coaching Academy) with the intention of sharing knowledge, and setting up a variety of camps and clinics for both players and coaches.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax's first stadium was built in 1911 out of wood and was called Het Houten Stadion (English: The Wooden Stadium).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax later also played in the Olympic Stadium built for the 1928 Summer Olympics hosted in Amsterdam.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] This stadium, designed by Jan Wils, is known in Dutch as *het Olympisch Stadion*.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 1934, Ajax moved to De Meer Stadion in east Amsterdam, close to the location of Het Houten Stadion.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] It was designed by architect and Ajax-member Daan Roodenburgh, who had also designed the club's first stadium.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] It could accommodate 29,500 spectators and Ajax continued to play there until 1996.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] For notable European and national fixtures, the club would often play at the Olympic Stadium, which could accommodate about twice the number of spectators.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 1996, Ajax moved to a new home ground in the southeast part of the city known as the Amsterdam Arena, since 2018 known as the Johan Cruyff Arena.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] This stadium was built by the Amsterdam city authority at a cost of $134 million.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The stadium is capable of holding 55,865 spectators.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The Arena has a retractable roof and set a trend for other modern stadiums built in Europe in the following years.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In the Netherlands, the Arena earned a reputation for a terrible grass pitch caused by the removable roof that, even when open, takes away too much sunlight and fresh air.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] During the 2008–09 season, ground staff introduced an artificial lighting system that finally reduced this problem considerably.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The much-loved former stadium, De Meer Stadion, was torn down in 1996 and the land was sold to the city council.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] A residential neighbourhood now occupies the area.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The only thing left of the old stadium are the letters "AJAX", which nowadays is in place on the façade of the entrance at the Johan Cruyff Arena.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] A replica of the same letters are at De Toekomst, near the Johan Cruyff Arena.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 1900, when the club was founded, the emblem of Ajax was just a picture of an Ajax player.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The crest was slightly altered following the club's promotion to the top division in 1911 to match the club's new outfits.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 1928, the club logo was introduced with the head of the Greek hero Ajax.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The logo was once again changed in 1990 into an abstract version of the previous one.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The new logo still sports the portrait of Ajax, but drawn with just 11 lines, symbolizing the 11 players of a football team.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] On 17 November 2024, Ajax announced on its official website that they would revert to the classic logo of 1928 from the 2025–26 season onward, making a comeback after 34 years.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax originally played in an all-black strip with a red sash tied around the players' waists, but that strip was soon replaced by a red/white striped shirt and black shorts.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Red, black and white are the three colours of the flag of Amsterdam.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Under manager Jack Kirwan, however, the club earned promotion to the top flight of Dutch football for the first time in 1911 (then the *Eerste Klasse* or 'First Class', later named the Eredivisie), Ajax was forced to change its colours because Sparta Rotterdam already had exactly the same outfit.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Special kits for away fixtures did not exist at the time and according to football association regulations the newcomers had to change their colours if two teams in the same league had identical uniforms.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax opted for white shorts and white shirt with a broad, vertical red stripe over chest and back, which remains their colours in the present day.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] AFC Ajax is the only Dutch club with an initial public offering (IPO).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The club is registered as a Naamloze vennootschap (N.V.) listed on the stock exchange Euronext Amsterdam, since 17 May 1998.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] With a launch price of ƒ25,- (Guilders) the club managed to a bring its total revenue up to €54 million (converted) in its first year on the market.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] After short-lived success, however, the rate dropped, at one point as low as €3.50.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Criticism was brought forth that the legal grid for a naamloze vennootschap would not be suitable for a Football club, and that the sports related ambitions would suffer from the new commercial interests of the now listed Ajax.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Shares of the company in the year 2008 were valued at approximately €5.90 per share.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 2008, a Commission under guidance of honorary member Uri Coronel concluded that the IPO was of no value to the club, and that measures should be taken to exit the stock exchange by purchasing back all public shares.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax's shirts have been sponsored by TDK from 1982 to 1991, and by ABN AMRO from 1991 to 2008.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] AEGON then replaced ABN AMRO as the new head sponsor for a period of seven years.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] On 1 April 2007, Ajax wore a different sponsor for the match against Heracles Almelo, *Florius*.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Florius is a banking programme launched by ABN AMRO who wanted it to be the shirt sponsor for one match.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] At the conclusion of the 2013–14 season, Ajax won the Football shirt of the Year award for its black and rose colored away shirt by Adidas.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The annual award was presented by Subside Sports, which had previously given the award to Internazionale, Juventus and the Belgium national team.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] It was Ajax's first time winning the award.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] On 7 November 2014, it was announced that Ajax had agreed to a four-and-a-half-year contract worth €8 million annually with Dutch cable operating company Ziggo as the new shirt sponsor for the club.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Having extended its contract with AEGON for half a season until December, the club featured *Fonds Gehandicaptensport*, a charitable fund for handicapped sports on its away shirts for a six-month period before transitioning to Ziggo in 2015.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Jong Ajax (*formerly more commonly known as Ajax 2*) is the reserve team of AFC Ajax.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The team is composed mostly of professional footballers, who are often recent graduates from the highest youth level (Ajax A1) serving their first professional contract as a reserve, or players who are otherwise unable to play in the first team.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Since 1992, Jong Ajax has competed in the Beloften Eredivisie, competing against other reserve teams such as Jong PSV, Jong Groningen or Jong AZ.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] They have won the Beloften Eredivisie title a record eight times, as well as the KNVB Reserve Cup three times, making them the most successful reserve squad in the Netherlands.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] By winning the Beloften Eredivisie title, Jong Ajax was able to qualify for the actual KNVB Cup, even advancing to the semi-finals on three occasions.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Its best result in the Dutch Cup was under manager Jan Olde Riekerink in 2001–02, when a semi-final loss to Utrecht in a Penalty shoot-out after extra time, which saw Utrecht advance, and thus preventing an Ajax–Jong Ajax Dutch Cup final.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The 2013–14 season marked the Jupiler League debut of the Ajax reserves' squad, Jong Ajax.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Previously playing in the Beloften Eredivisie (a separate league for reserve teams, not included in the Dutch professional or amateur league structure), players were allowed to move around freely between the reserve team and the first team during the season.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] This is no longer the case as Jong Ajax now registers and fields a separate squad from that of Ajax first team for the Eerste Divisie, the second tier of professional football in the Netherlands.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Its home matches are played at Sportpark De Toekomst, except for the occasional match in the Johan Cruyff Arena.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Furthermore, the team is not eligible for promotion to the Eredivisie or to participate in the KNVB Cup.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Jong Ajax was joined in the Eerste Divisie by Jong Twente and Jong PSV, reserve teams who have also moved from the Beloften Eredivisie to the Eerste Divisie, in place of VV Katwijk, SC Veendam and AGOVV Apeldoorn, increasing the total number of teams in the Jupiler League from 18 to 20.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax reserve squad Jong Ajax left the Beloften Eredivisie in 2013, having held a 21-year tenure in the reserves league, having also won the league title a record eight times (1994, 1996, 1998, 2001, 2002, 2004, 2005, 2009).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax Vrouwen (*English: Ajax Women*) is the women's team of Ajax, competing in the women's eredivisie, the highest level of women's football in the Netherlands.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Founded on 18 May 2012, the women's team saw Ajax attracting many of the Netherlands top talents, with International players such as Anouk Hoogendijk, Daphne Koster and Petra Hogewoning joining the Amsterdam club in its maiden season in women's professional football.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The team won its first piece of silverware when they defeated PSV/FC Eindhoven 2–1 in the final of the KNVB Women's Cup.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax Amateurs, better known as **Ajax Zaterdag**, is a Dutch amateur football club founded 18 March 1900.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] It is the amateur team of the professional club AFC Ajax, playing its home matches at the Sportpark De Toekomst training grounds to a capacity of 5,000.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The team was promoted from the Eerste Klasse to the Hoofdklasse ahead of the 2011–12 season, the league in which it is currently competing.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The team has won the Eerste Klasse title twice, as well as the *KNVB District Cup West I on two occasions as well.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Furthermore, Ajax Zaterdag has also managed to qualify for the KNVB Cup on its own accord on three occasions, namely in 2004, 2005, 2008 and 2021.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] They even advanced to the second round, before bowing out to Vitesse on 24 September 2008.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax HVA (1922–1972) was the baseball team of Ajax founded in 1922, and competed as founding members of the Honkbal Hoofdklasse, the top flight of professional baseball in the Netherlands.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax won the national baseball title a total of four times (1924, 1928, 1942, 1948) before the club opted to no longer field a baseball team, and to focus solely on football in 1972.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax spent a total of 50 years at the top flight of Baseball in the Netherlands from 1922 to 1972.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The dissolution of Ajax baseball club resulted in the players finding a new sponsor in a mustard manufacturing company called Luycks, while merging with the Diemen Giants to become the Luycks Giants, thus replacing both former clubs.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 2016, Ajax launched an esports team, with Koen Weijland as the club's first signing, making its debut on the Global stage of professional gaming.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] They have since signed the likes of Dani Hagebeuk, Lev Vinken, Joey Calabro and Bob van Uden, the latter spent his first season on loan to the esports team of Japanese club Sagan Tosu.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Feyenoord from Rotterdam is Ajax's archrival.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Every year both clubs play the *De Klassieker* ("The Classic"), a match between the teams from the two largest cities of the Netherlands.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Till the 1973/74-season, Ajax and Feyenoord were the only two clubs in the Netherlands who were able to clinch national titles, as well as achieve continental and even global success.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] From the 1974/75-season on, PSV (Eindhoven) and AZ (Alkmaar) too, competed with Ajax and Feyenoord.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] A meeting between the two clubs became the measure for who was truly the best club in the Netherlands.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The *Klassieker* is the most famous of all the rivalries in the Netherlands and the matches are always sold out.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The fixture is seen in the public eye as "the graceful and elegant football of Ajax, against the indomitable fighting spirit of Feyenoord"; the confidence of the capital city versus the blue collar mentality of Rotterdam.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Matches are known for their tension and violence, both on and off the pitch.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Over the years, several violent incidents have taken place involving rival supporters, leading to the current prohibition of away supporters in both stadiums.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The lowest point was reached on 23 March 1997, when supporters of both clubs met on a field near Beverwijk, where Ajax-supporter Carlo Picornie was fatally injured, the incident is commonly referred to as the "Battle of Beverwijk".
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] PSV is also a rival of Ajax, but in terms of tension and rivalry, these matches are not as loaded as the duels with Feyenoord.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The rivalry has existed for some time with PSV and stems from various causes, such as the different interpretations of whether current national and international successes of both clubs correlates and the supposed opposition between the Randstad and the province.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The matches between these two teams is commonly referred to as "De Topper" ("The Topper"), and involves the two most trophy-laden sides in Dutch football and is essentially a clash of two competing schools of thought in Dutch football.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Historically, PSV compete with a workmanlike ethic, preferring a more robust 4–3–1–2 or 4–2–3–1, typically shunning the frivolous 4–3–3 approach favoured in Amsterdam.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] While Rinus Michels and Johan Cruyff helped to innovate Total Football in the sixties and seventies, a different philosophy was honed in Eindhoven by Kees Rijvers and Guus Hiddink in the late 1970s and '80s.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] This in turn has created one of the more philosophical rivalries in football, an ideological battleground, which is gradually becoming as heated and intense as the matches Ajax and Feyenoord partake in.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] A more recent rivalry has developed with AZ from nearby Alkmaar.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Since both Ajax and AZ are situated in North Holland province, the fixture is often referred to as "De Noord-Hollandse derby" ("The North Holland derby").
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Although the clubs first met in the 1960s, the rivalry intensified when AZ won the Dutch championship in 2009.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The derby has since become a key clash in the Dutch football season, often with high stakes and impact on the league.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Although many Ajax supporters regard AZ as their "little brother", it remains a competitive and emotionally charged fixture.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The supporters have clashed several times since 2009.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In December 2024, for example, Ajax supporters attacked an AZ pub in Alkmaar during a derby match.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] A notable incident occurred on 21 December 2011 during a KNVB Cup match.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] An Ajax supporter ran onto the pitch and attacked AZ goalkeeper Esteban Alvarado, who defended himself by kicking the pitch invader twice and received a straight red card from referee Bas Nijhuis.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] AZ coach Gertjan Verbeek took his players off the pitch in protest, following which the match was definitively abandoned.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The sides furthermore compete for staff and youth prospects in the North Holland region.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] When technical director Martin van Geel left AZ for Ajax in 2006, AZ director Dirk Scheringa banned him from the club's stadium.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax have several other rivalries, although in most cases the sentiment is mostly felt by the opposition and is more directed towards Ajax, with one of them being Utrecht.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Although the rivalry is more felt on the Utrecht side than with Ajax, matchups between the two sides are often quite intense.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Both teams have fanatic supporters, and clashes off the pitch are more often the rule than the exception.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The same goes for ADO Den Haag, with both supporter groups often getting in conflicts, when ADO-Hooligans set fire to the supporters home of Ajax, and Ajax hooligans subsequently broke into the supporters home of ADO, tensions between the two clubs rose.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 2006, supporters from both clubs were banned from attending away matches for five years due to frequent violent outbreaks and clashes.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Further teams who share a rivalry with Ajax include Twente, Vitesse and Groningen.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Past rivalries include local Amsterdam derbies between Ajax and clubs such as Blauw-Wit, DWS and De Volewijckers (which later merged to become FC Amsterdam in 1972).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] However, the tension between the local sides lessened as the division of the clubs through playing in different leagues over time became greater.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Years of not competing in the same league resulted in less frequent match-ups, until tensions finally settled between the Amsterdam clubs.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The last Amsterdam derby to take place in an official league match was when Ajax defeated FC Amsterdam 5–1 on 19 March 1978.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Ajax is known for having fanatic core supporter-groups, of which F-Side and VAK410 are the most famous.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The F-Side was founded on 3 October 1976, and is situated right behind the goal in the Johan Cruyff Arena, on the southern end of the stadium in rows 125–129.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Its name is derived from the group's former location on the F-side of the old De Meer Stadion.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The F-side supporters are responsible for a big part of the atmosphere in the stadium, and are also known for rioting during and after matches.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] If in any match Ajax should win the coin toss, the second half of the match Ajax always play towards the south-end of the stadium.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] VAK410 (English: Row 410) was founded in 2001 and is situated in the Zuidhoek (*South corner*) of the stadium on the upper ring in rows 424–425.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The group was originally situated on the North-West side of the stadium in row 410, from where it derives its name, until relocating to their current place in the stands in 2008.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Members of VAK410 are known to perform various stunts, which include massive banners, to enhance the atmosphere in the stadium.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Neither F-Side or VAK410 have seats in their sections of the stadium, and both groups stand for the duration of the match.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Through the official *Football Top 20* of Dutch sports research group *SPORT+MARKT*, it was revealed in 2010 that Ajax had approximately 7.1 million supporters throughout Europe.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] This is significantly more than rivals Feyenoord and PSV (each 1.6 and 1.3 million, respectively), which puts Ajax as the club with the 15th-most supporters across Europe.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The study also revealed that approximately 39% of the Netherlands were Ajax supporters.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] It is noteworthy that not all stadiums share the capacity of the Johan Cruyff Arena.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The Supporters Club Ajax (Dutch: *Supportersvereniging Ajax*) is officially the largest supporters club in the Netherlands with 94,000 members.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Founded on 7 May 1992, the supporters club organize big monthly events throughout the Netherlands, and particularly around the official Ajax Open Training Day, which attracts thousands of supporters each year.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Furthermore, the supporters group is responsible for the Ajax Life website, as well as the fanzine which is issued 20 times a year.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 2006, the AFCA Supportersclub was introduced as the club's second official supporters' association, through the merger of the Onafhankelijke Fanclub Ajax (OFA) and the Ajax Supporters Delegatie (ASD).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The AFCA Supportersclub has a reported 42,000 members, as well as a former member on the Board of Administration of Ajax, in Ronald Pieloor.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The third official supporters club is the Ajax Business Associates (ABA).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Founded in 1991 the ABA is the Business club of Ajax.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Members occupy the skyboxes in the Stadium and can make use of the clubs' amenities and luxury suites including the ABA club and lounge.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The ABA is also responsible for hosting the annual Ajax Business Golf Trophy, an amateur golf tournament where several active and former Ajax players, as well as prominent people and members of the ABA, participate.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] This graph displays the average attendance for home matches of Ajax from 1988 to 2018, whereby the difference in capacity of the De Meer Stadion and the Johan Cruyff Arena (opened in 1996) is clearly visible.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Historically, Ajax was popularly seen as having "Jewish roots".
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The city of Amsterdam was historically referred to as a Mokum city, Mokum (מקום) being the Yiddish word for "place" or "safe haven", though 75% of the Jewish citizens were killed during the Holocaust.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] This Jewish imagery eventually became a central part of Ajax fans' culture.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] At one point, ringtones of "Hava Nagila", a Hebrew folk song, could be downloaded from the club's official website.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Beginning in the 1980s, fans of Ajax's rivals escalated their antisemitic rhetoric, chanting slogans like "Hamas, Hamas/Jews to the gas" ("Hamas, hamas, joden aan het gas"), hissing to imitate the flow of gas, giving Nazi salutes, and other things.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The eventual result was that many genuinely Jewish Ajax fans stopped going to games.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In the 2000s, the club began trying to persuade fans to drop its Jewish image.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] In 2013, a documentary titled *Superjews* was released by NTR and Viewpoint Productions which premiered at the International Documentary Film Festival Amsterdam (IDFA).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] The film was directed by Nirit Peled, an Israeli living in Amsterdam, and an independent film maker who offers a very personal view into the game, the lore of Ajax and its relation to Judaism from both the supporters as well as from a Jewish perspective.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Before and after a UEFA Europa League game between Israeli team Maccabi Tel Aviv and Ajax on 7 November 2024 in the Johan Cruyff Arena, tensions surrounding the Gaza war erupted into violence.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Note: Flags indicate national team as defined under FIFA eligibility rules; some limited exceptions apply.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p01] Players may hold more than one non-FIFA nationality.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Ajax also won in 1972, however UEFA only sanctioned the UEFA Super Cup for the first time in 1973 so the 1972 edition was an unofficial one.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Played against Rangers, winners of the 1971–72 European Cup Winners' Cup, it went ahead as 'a celebration of the Centenary of Rangers F.C.' (see below) because Rangers was serving a one-year ban at the time, imposed by UEFA for the misbehaviour of its fans.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] That victory meant Ajax had won every tournament (5 in total) they entered that year, a feat Celtic achieved in 1967 (with 6 trophies), Barcelona in 2009 (6 trophies), and Bayern in 2020 (also 6 trophies).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Ajax have won numerous friendly tournaments, unsanctioned by UEFA or FIFA, including the Amsterdam Tournament, Bruges Matins Trophy, Trofeo Santiago Bernabéu, Eusébio Cup, Ted Bates Trophy, Jalkapalloturnaus and Chippie Polar Cup (*for a complete list, see: list of AFC Ajax honours*).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Ajax have a total of 50 honorary club members, from people who have been invested within the club's administrative engagements, to committed players who have excelled in the athletic department.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Nine members still remain, including Louis van Gaal.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Below is a table with Ajax's domestic results since the introduction of the Eredivisie in 1956.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] The Club van 100 is the official list of football players who have appeared in one hundred or more official matches for AFC Ajax.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] The club currently has a total of over 150 members.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] The record for league appearances is held by **Mr.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Ajax** himself Sjaak Swart, who appeared in 463 league matches for Ajax.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] There is a beneficiary team called Lucky Ajax, which was initiated by Sjaak Swart.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Lucky Ajax participate in at least one match a year, usually in the name of charity, and commonly at football ceremonies to bid farewell to retiring players.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] One of the prerequisites for playing on Lucky Ajax, which is invitational only, is that you are a member of the Club van 100, having made at least 100 official match appearances for Ajax in the first team of the club.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Lucky Ajax is a beneficiary team that was initiated by Sjaak Swart in the seventies, competing in at least one match a year, usually in the name of charity and/or to bid farewell to retiring former Ajax players.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] The team is made up of various members of the Club van 100 of Ajax who will come out of retirement for this match to face the Ajax squad that is current of that year.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Past participants have included Barry Hulshoff, Sonny Silooy, Simon Tahamata, Ronald Koeman, Tscheu La Ling, Gerrie Mühren, John van 't Schip, Brian Roy, Stanley Menzo, Peter van Vossen and Fred Grim.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] The name Lucky Ajax is derived from the famous "Lucky Ajax" nickname from how people used to refer to the club when Ajax would either win a match by chance, by a decision of a referee, or by coincidence such as was said to be the case during the infamous *Mistwedstrijd* ("Fog Match").
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] As of the 2007–08 season, no player could wear the number 14 shirt at Ajax after the club decided to retire the shirt out of respect for Johan Cruyff, "the legendary number fourteen".
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Cruyff himself laughed off the tribute, saying the club had to let its best player play with number 14.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Spanish midfielder Roger was the last player to wear the number.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Marvin Zeegelaar wore the shirt number in preparation for the 2011–12 season in one preseason match, while Aras Özbiliz wore the number 14 shirt in one pre-season match ahead of the 2011–12 season as well.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] The club stated that this was, in fact, not done in error.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Below is a list of all players to wear the number 14 shirt since Johan Cruyff's departure.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Established in 1975 as the Amsterdam 700 Tournament to celebrate 700 years of history in the city.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] The tournament was hosted annually each summer by Ajax until 1992, when the last edition of the original tournament was played.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] It returned in 1999 with the backing of the International Event Partnership (IEP).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Four teams participated in the competition, played in a league format since 1986.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Since its return, the tournament used an unusual point scoring system.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] As with most league competitions, three points were awarded for a win, one for a draw, and none for a loss.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] An additional point, however, was awarded for each goal scored.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] The system was designed to reward teams that adopted a more attacking style of play.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Each entrant played two matches, with the winner being the club that finished at the top of the table.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] The original competition was held at Het Olympisch Stadion where Ajax played the bigget games until 1996.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] The Amsterdam Arena (now Johan Cruyff Arena) played host to the event since its return until the last edition was played in 2009.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Ajax is the most successful team of the tournament, having won it a record ten times, while Benfica from Portugal was the last team to win the tournament, in 2009.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Each Summer the city of Amsterdam and Ajax invite U-19 teams from various top clubs from around the World to participate in the tournament.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Seven teams are invited and play in the competition every year.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Over the years, clubs such as Barcelona, Juventus, Chelsea and Real Madrid have had their senior youth teams participate in the tournament.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Cruzeiro from Brazil is the most successful club in the history of the tournament, having won it three times in total.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Established in 2010, the AEGON Future Cup is an international friendly tournament for Under-17 youth teams, which is organized by AFC Ajax and their main sponsor, the insurance company AEGON.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] The tournament is held each year at the Johan Cruyff Arena and at the Sportpark De Toekomst, the team's training ground, which also inspired the name of the competition, since *De Toekomst* in Dutch means The Future.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Every year during the Easter weekend, six U-17 teams are invited to participate in the competition, while the seventh place for the contesters is reserved for the winners of the "Craques Mongeral AEGON Future Cup" in Brazil, the sister competition of the tournament in South America.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Youth teams from top clubs such as Manchester United, Bayern Munich, Milan and many more have participated in the competition over the years.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/afc-ajax-p02] Ajax is the most successful club of the tournament, having won the trophy a total of five times.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/ajet] AnadoluJet was created on 23 April 2008 as a trademark by Turkish Airlines.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/ajet] In March 2020, the brand was reconfigured to apply to the entire Turkish Airlines international route network operating from Istanbul Sabiha Gökçen International Airport, consisting of over 20 routes.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/ajet] Turkish Airlines said in a stock market disclosure that the new company was incorporated on 14 July 2023, with an initial paid-up capital of TRY450 million (EUR15.75 million), and will continue operating as a low-cost carrier.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/ajet] In November 2023, Turkish Airlines unveiled the airline's new branding and livery.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/ajet] The airline was to operate as a fully owned low-cost subsidiary of Turkish Airlines.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/ajet] It also announced plans to acquire a separate AOC for the carrier.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/ajet] On 2 January 2024, AnadoluJet received its own independent air operator's certificate ahead of its rebranding due in early 2024.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/ajet] It is subsequently rebranded into its new corporate identity as AJet on 1 April 2024.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/ajet] AJet operates flights to domestic and international destinations in several countries across Europe, Asia and Africa.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/ajet] AJet additionally maintains codeshare agreements with its parent company Turkish Airlines.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/ajet] And they also restored 2 Airbus A320ceos as of August 1, before that, it was retired temporarily and only Turkish Airlines livery was used.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol is the principal hub for KLM and its regional affiliate KLM Cityhopper, as well as for Martinair.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The airport also serves as an operating base for Corendon Dutch Airlines, easyJet, Transavia, TUI fly Netherlands, and Vueling.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol opened on 16 September 1916 as a military airbase.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The end of the First World War also saw the beginning of civilian use of Schiphol Airport, and the airport eventually lost its military role completely.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] By 1940, Schiphol had four asphalt runways at 45-degree angles.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The airport was captured by the German military that same year and renamed *Fliegerhorst Schiphol*.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The airport was destroyed by bombing, but at the end of the war, the airfield was soon rebuilt.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] In 1949, it was decided that Schiphol was to become the primary airport of the Netherlands.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol Airport was voted the best airport in Western Europe in 2020.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The name *Sciphol* appears in an official document from 1447.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol Airport ranked as Europe's third busiest and the world's eleventh busiest by total passenger traffic in 2017 (12th in 2016, 14th in 2015, 2014 and 2013, and 16th in 2012).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] It also ranks as the world's fifth busiest by international passenger traffic and the world's sixteenth busiest for cargo tonnage.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] A record 71,706,999 passengers passed through the airport in 2019.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol's main competitors in terms of passenger traffic and cargo throughput are London Heathrow, Frankfurt, Madrid, Paris–Charles de Gaulle and Istanbul.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] In 2019, 70.5% of passengers using the airport flew to and from Europe, 10.6% to and from North America, and 10.1% to and from Asia; cargo volume was mainly between Schiphol and Asia (46.3%) and North America (17.6%).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] In 2019, 102 carriers provided a total of 332 destinations on a regular basis.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] In 2024, Schiphol handled 66.8 million passengers and almost 474,000 flights, remaining below traffic levels before the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The airport is built as one large terminal (a single-terminal concept), split into three departure halls, which connect again once airside.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The most recent of these was completed in 1994 and expanded in 2007 with a new section, called Terminal 4, although it is not considered a separate building.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] A new pier is to be opened in 2019 with a terminal extension planned to be operational by 2023.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Plans for further terminal and gate expansion exist, including the construction of a separate new terminal between the Zwanenburgbaan and Polderbaan runways that would end the one-terminal concept.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Because of heavy traffic and high landing fees (due to the limit of 500,000 flights a year), some low-cost carriers decided to move their flights to smaller airports, such as Rotterdam The Hague Airport and Eindhoven Airport.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Many low-cost carriers, such as EasyJet and Ryanair, however, continue to operate at Schiphol, using the low-cost H pier.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] In 2015, Lelystad Airport was allowed to expand, aimed at accommodating some of the low-cost and leisure flights currently operating out of Schiphol, eventually taking up to 45,000 flights a year.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] To combat complaints from the community in Schiphol, Amsterdam Airport is advocating the prohibition of private jets, with the aim of minimizing noise and environmental pollution.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The airport also intends to restrict takeoffs between midnight and 06:00 and landings between midnight and 05:00.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Before 1852, the entire polder of Haarlemmermeer in which the airport lies was a large lake with some shallow areas.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] There are multiple stories of how the place got its name.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The most popular story is that in the shallow waters, sudden violent storms could claim many ships.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Winds were particularly strong in the Schiphol area since the prevailing wind direction is from the southwest, and Schiphol lies in the northeastern corner of the lake.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] In English, *schiphol* translates to 'ship hole', a reference to many ships supposedly lost in the lake.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] When the lake was reclaimed, however, no shipwrecks were found.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Another possible origin of the name is the word *scheepshaal*.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] A *scheepshaal* is a ditch or small canal in which ships would be towed from one lake to another.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] A third explanation would be that the name is derived from the words *schip hol*.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] This is a low-lying area of land (*hol*) from where wood would be obtained to build ships.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] After the lake was dredged in the mid-1800s, a fortification named Fort Schiphol was built in the area, which was part of the Stelling van Amsterdam defence works.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol opened on 16 September 1916 as a military airbase, with a few barracks and a field serving as a platform and runways.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] When civil aircraft started to use the field (17 December 1920), it was often called *Schiphol-les-bains*.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The Fokker aircraft manufacturer started a factory near Schiphol airport in 1919.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The end of the First World War also saw the beginning of civilian use of Schiphol Airport and the airport eventually lost its military role completely.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] By 1940, Schiphol had four asphalt runways at 45-degree angles, all 1,020 m (3,350 ft) or less.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] A large number of anti-aircraft defences were installed in the vicinity of the airport, and fake decoy airfields were constructed in the vicinity near Bennebroek, Vijfhuizen, and Vogelenzang to try to confuse Allied bombers.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Despite these defences, the airfield was still bombed intensively; an exceptionally heavy attack on 13 December 1943 caused so much damage that it rendered the airfield unusable as an active base.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] After that, it served only as an emergency landing field until the Germans themselves destroyed the remnants of the airfield at the start of Operation Market Garden.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] At the end of the war, the airfield was quickly restored: the first aircraft, a Douglas DC-3, landed on 8 July 1945.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] A new terminal building was completed in 1949, and it was decided that Schiphol was to become the primary airport of the Netherlands.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The expansion came at the cost of a small town called Rijk, which was demolished to make room for the growing airport.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The name of this town is remembered in the name of the present Schiphol-Rijk industrial estate.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] In 1967, Schiphol expanded even further with a new terminal area at its current location.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Most of the 1967 terminal is still in use today (Departure Halls 1 and 2), as are parts of the original piers (now called C, D, and E).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Dutch designer Benno Wissing created signage for Schiphol Airport, well known for its clear writing and thorough colour-coding; to avoid confusion, he prohibited any other signage in the shades of yellow and green used.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The new terminal building replaced the older facilities once located on what is now the east side of the airport.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The A-pier (now C-pier) of the airport was modified in 1970 to allow Boeing 747 aircraft to use the boarding gates.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] A new pier (D, now called F) opened in 1977, dedicated to handling wide-body aircraft.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The first railway station at the airport was opened in 1978.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The construction of a new air traffic control tower was completed in 1991, as the existing tower could no longer oversee all of the airport, as it was further expanded.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Departure Hall 3 was added to the terminal in 1993, as was another pier, G-pier.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] New wayfinding signage was designed that year as well by Paul Mijksenaar.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] A sixth runway was completed at quite some distance west of the rest of airport in 2003 and was nicknamed the Polderbaan, with the connecting taxiway bridge crossing the A5 motorway.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The distance of this runway means that taxiing to and from this runway can take between 10 and 20 minutes.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] It also required the construction of an additional air traffic control tower, as the primary tower is too far away to oversee this part of the airfield.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] On 25 February 2005, a diamond robbery occurred at Schiphol's cargo terminal.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The thieves used a stolen KLM van to gain airside access.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The estimated value of the stones was around 75 million euros, making it one of the largest diamond robberies ever.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Later in 2005, a fire broke out at the airport's detention centre, killing 11 people and injuring 15.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The complex was holding 350 people at the time of the incident.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Results from the investigation almost one year later showed that fire safety precautions were not in force.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] A national outrage resulted in the resignation of Justice Minister Piet Hein Donner (CDA) and Mayor Hartog of Haarlemmermeer.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Spatial Planning Minister Sybilla Dekker (VVD) resigned as well because she bore responsibility for safety failings cited in the report.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] In the summer of 2022, the airport suffered the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on commercial air transport.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] It experienced extraordinarily long delays and a large number of cancelled flights, which led to a recession of air traffic and subsequently to a shortage of security staff and a walkout of baggage handlers.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Queues for security check-in were reported to last for 5 hours, and many passengers missed their flights.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The CEO of Schiphol Group, Dick Benschop, was forced to resign.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] In 2024, Schiphol saw an 8% increase in passenger traffic and an 8.2% rise in cargo volume compared to 2023.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Also in 2024, Royal Schiphol Group announced a €6 billion infrastructure investment plan, the largest in the airport's history.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Planned improvements included the renovations of Pier C, Lounge 1, the baggage system, and passenger walkways, lifts, and bridges.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The Lounge 1 expansion was completed by November 2024, with 5,000 square meters of additional passenger space and a new plaza.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol uses a one-terminal concept, where all facilities are located under a single roof, radiating from the central plaza, Schiphol Plaza.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The terminal is divided into three sections or halls designated 1, 2, and 3.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The piers and concourses of each hall are connected so that it is possible, on both sides of security or border inspection, to walk between piers and halls, although border control separates Schengen from non-Schengen areas.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The exception to this is the low-cost pier M: once airside (past security), passengers cannot access any other areas.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol Airport has approximately 223 boarding gates including eighteen double jetway gates used for widebody aircraft.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The airport adopted a distinctive design, with the second jetway extending over the aircraft wing, hanging from a steel cantilever structure.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Gradual refurbishments have seen these jetways replaced with a more conventional layout, with the last two taken out of use in November 2024.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Three gates have been modified to accommodate the Airbus A380.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Emirates was the first airline to fly the A380 to Schiphol in August 2012, deploying the aircraft on its double daily Dubai–Amsterdam service.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] China Southern Airlines also used the A380 on its Beijing–Amsterdam route before removing the type from service at the end of 2022, leaving Emirates as the sole A380 operator at Schiphol Airport as of 2023.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The 1st floor hosts the luggage check-in lines, many of them automated, as well as various duty-free refund booths.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Available seating is limited on this floor.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Notable public artworks in the airport include the Schiphol clock by Maarten Baas, in which a man behind a translucent screen appears to paint the minutes of an analog clock by hand.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Departure Hall 1 consists of Piers B and C, both of which are dedicated Schengen areas and share D-pier with Departure Hall 2.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Pier B has 12 gates and Pier C has 13 gates.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Departure Hall 2 consists of Piers D and E.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Pier D is the largest pier and has two levels.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The lower floor houses non-Schengen flights, and the upper floor is used for Schengen flights.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] By using stairs, the same jetways are used to access the aircraft.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schengen gates are numbered beginning with D-59; non-Schengen gates are numbered from D-1 to D-57.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Pier E is a dedicated non-Schengen area and has fourteen gates.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] It is typically home to SkyTeam hub airlines Delta Air Lines and KLM, along with other members, such as China Airlines and China Southern Airlines.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Other Middle Eastern and Asian airlines such as Air Astana, EVA Air, Etihad Airways, and Iran Air also typically operate out of Pier E.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Departure Hall 3 consists of three piers: F, G, and H/M.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Pier F has eight gates and is typically dominated by SkyTeam members such as primary airline KLM, Kenya Airways, China Airlines, China Southern Airlines, and other members.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Piers H and M are physically one concourse consisting of seven shared gates and are home to low-cost airlines.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Operating completely separately, H handles non-Schengen flights while M is dedicated to flights within the Schengen area.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Gates G9, E18 and E24 (E24 refurbished in 2019) are equipped to handle daily Airbus A380 service by Emirates.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] China Southern Airlines also operated the type before withdrawing it from service at the end of 2022, leaving Emirates as the only A380 operator at Schiphol as of 2023.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] A new general aviation terminal was opened in 2011 on the east side of the airport, operated as the *KLM Jet Center*.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The new terminal building has a floorspace of 6,000 m2 (65,000 sq ft); 1,000 m2 (11,000 sq ft) for the actual terminal and lounges, 4,000 m2 (43,000 sq ft) for office space and 1,000 m2 (11,000 sq ft) for parking.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The centre and its activities were sold to the Swiss company Jet Aviation in October 2018 and was rebranded as Jet Aviation Amsterdam.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The Rijksmuseum operates an annex at the airport, offering a small overview of both classical and contemporary art.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Admission to the exhibits is free, but requires a plane ticket as it is situated in the passenger transit zone.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] In the summer of 2010, Schiphol Airport Library opened alongside the museum, providing passengers access to a collection of 1,200 books (translated into 29 languages) by Dutch authors on subjects relating to the country's history and culture.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The 89.9 m2 (968 sq ft) library offers e-books and music by Dutch artists and composers that can be downloaded free of charge to a laptop or mobile device.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] For aviation enthusiasts, Amsterdam Airport Schiphol has a large rooftop viewing area, called the Panoramaterras.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] It is not accessible to connecting passengers unless they first exit the airport.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Enthusiasts and the public can enter, free of charge, from the airport's landside.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Since June 2011, it has been the location for a KLM Cityhopper Fokker 100, modified to be a viewing exhibit.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Besides the Panoramaterras, Schiphol has other spotting sites, especially along the newest Polderbaan runway and at the McDonald's restaurant at the north side of the airport.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol has its own mortuary, where the dead can be handled and kept before departure or after arrival.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Between October 2006 and 2019, people could also hold a wedding ceremony at Schiphol.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] In 2012, Schiphol Group announced an expansion of Schiphol, featuring a new pier.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Pier A will be part of Departure Hall 1, which already has Pier B (14 gates) and Pier C (21 gates).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The new Pier A will have five narrow-body gates and will initially have three wide-body gates, with two more planned for a later phase.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The new Pier A is under construction to the southwest of Pier B, in an area formerly used as a freight platform.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Pier A is planned to be mainly used for flights within Europe.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The expansions were originally supposed to cost about 500 million Euro.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The first construction activities were originally expected to start in 2017 with an estimated opening in 2019.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] However, the construction of the new pier has been delayed several times and due to a conflict between the airport and the construction consortium, the construction was halted in November 2021.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol was disappointed in the construction speed and the rising of the total cost, although insiders announced that a design flaw was made and the entire construction needed to be reinforced.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] A new tendering procedure was started to find a new constructor in 2022, once found a new completion date will be announced.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] In July 2024, Schiphol announced that the new terminal is expected to open in April 2027.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The total amount of the investment increased to 1.393 million Euro primarily due to repair work, delays and a longer project duration.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] To handle future growth in passengers, Schiphol will further expand by building a fourth terminal hall with facilities for both departures and arrivals.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] From this new building, direct access will be made to Schiphol Plaza, continuing the one-terminal concept.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] When finished in 2023, Schiphol will be able to handle over 70 million passengers.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Due to rapid growth of Schengen passengers during 2016, Schiphol was however forced to rapidly build a temporary departure hall which opened in March 2017.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Due to the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic the construction of the fourth terminal hall has been postponed for at least two years.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The airport has expanded the number of uniform platforms, and places to stow airplanes, in recent years in two phases.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] A third phase is planned to expand the number of wide-body platforms to a total of twelve, with planned completion in the period 2022–2026.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol, together with the public transport authority Amsterdam, is going to transform its train- and bus station.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The train station will be getting more entrances and the bus station will be completely renewed with a planned opening date in 2025.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] A connection to the Amsterdam Metro network has been a subject of discussion and speculation since at least the 1990s.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] In preparation for this, a piece of land has been acquired from Chipshol.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] As of 2022, the project had not moved past the proposal stage.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol's growth is hampered by slot restrictions from the government.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] For reasons of safety and noise reduction, Schiphol was allowed to have no more than 500,000 aircraft movements until the end of 2020.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] A proposal to increase the limit to 540,000 movements from 2021 onwards was postponed until a new government was formed after the elections in March 2021.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] As Schiphol nearly approached the limit of 500,000 in the last few years, the slot restrictions have hindered airlines to settle at Schiphol.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Among airlines that have expressed interest in flying at Schiphol are Atlantic Airways, Cyprus Airways, Somon Air and SpiceJet.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The Schiphol air traffic control tower, with a height of 101 m (331 ft), was the tallest in the world when constructed in 1991.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol is geographically one of the world's lowest major commercial airports.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The lowest point sits at 3.4 m (11 ft) below sea level: 1.4 m (4.5 ft) below the Dutch Normaal Amsterdams Peil (NAP).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The runways are around 3 m (9.8 ft) below NAP.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] It is one of only eleven airports worldwide below sea level, the fifth lowest with scheduled flights, and the third lowest with international flights.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol has six runways, one of which is used mainly by general aviation.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The airport covers a total area of 2,787 hectares (6,887 acres) of land.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Typical peak moments at Schiphol Airport are between 09:00 and 11:00, and between 13:00 and 15:00 for departures, with up to 58 departures between 14:00 and 15:00 on a typical weekday (a departure nearly every minute).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The peak moment for arrivals is between 08:00 and 09:00 (with up to 52 arrivals on weekdays).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The TransPort Building on the Schiphol Airport property houses the head offices of Martinair and transavia.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Construction of the building, which has 10,800 m2 (116,000 sq ft) of rentable space, began on 17 March 2009.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol Group and the architect firm Paul de Ruiter designed the building, while construction firm De Vries & Verburg constructed the building.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The World Trade Center Schiphol Airport houses the head office of SkyTeam, local offices of China Southern Airlines and Iran Air.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The head office of Schiphol Group, the airport's operator, is located on the airport property.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The original control tower of Schiphol Airport, which the airport authorities had moved slightly from its original location, now houses a restaurant.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The area Schiphol-Rijk includes the head office of TUI fly Netherlands.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] At one time, KLM had its head office briefly on the grounds of Schiphol Airport.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Its current head office in nearby Amstelveen had a scheduled completion at the end of 1970.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Previously, Martinair had its head office in the Schiphol Center (Dutch: *Schiphol Centrum*) at Schiphol Airport.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Formerly, the head office of Transavia was in the Building Triport III at Schiphol Airport.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] NLM CityHopper and later KLM Cityhopper previously had their head offices in Schiphol Airport building 70.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The Convair Building, with its development beginning after a parcel was earmarked for its development in 1999, houses various KLM offices, including KLM Recruitment Services and the head office of KLM Cityhopper.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Nippon Cargo Airlines has its Europe regional headquarters at Schiphol.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The National Aerospace Museum Aviodome–Schiphol was previously located at Schiphol.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The Nederlandse Spoorwegen (NS), the national Dutch train operator, has a major passenger railway station directly underneath the passenger terminal complex that offers transportation 24 hours a day into the four major cities Amsterdam, Utrecht, The Hague and Rotterdam.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] There are efficient and often direct services to many other cities in the country.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol is also a stop for the Eurostar international high-speed train (formerly known as Thalys), connecting the airport directly to Antwerp, Brussels and Paris Gare du Nord, as well as to Bourg St Maurice (winter) and Marseille (summer).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The Intercity-Brussels (also named the "Beneluxtrein") to Antwerp and Brussels stops at the airport.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Amsterdam Airport Schiphol is also easily accessible by bus, as many services call or terminate at the bus station located in front of the terminal building.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] EVA Air provides private bus services from Schiphol to Belgium for its Belgium-based customers.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The service goes to Saint-Gilles, Brussels (near the Brussels-South (Midi) railway station) and Berchem, Antwerp (near Antwerp-Berchem bus station).
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] The service is operated by Reizen Lauwers NV on behalf of EVA Air.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] Schiphol Airport can easily be reached by car via the A4 and A9 motorways.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/amsterdam-airport-schiphol] While most roads leading to the airport are forbidden for bicycles, it is possible to reach the airport by bicycle via bicycle paths.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] 's-Hertogenbosch station opened on 1 November 1868 as the northern terminus of the southern part of the Utrecht–Boxtel railway (*Staatslijn H*), with service south to Boxtel.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] Only in 1870 were the two parts of Line H joined, allowing for direct service to Utrecht Centraal.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] As the town was a fortress at the time, the station was designed with attack in mind; its wood truss construction allowed it to be dismantled or damaged with minimal waste.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] 's-Hertogenbosch station was further expanded upon the opening of the Tilburg–Nijmegen railway, making it an important railway junction.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] In 1896, the original station was replaced with a large brick structure designed by Eduard Cuypers.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] The station was relocated a few hundred metres south of the original, along with the realignment of the tracks to the west.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] The second 's-Hertogenbosch station was characterised by its neo-Renaissance style, with a second floor for railway employees.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] During World War II, at 16 September 1944, the station caught fire and burnt down; it was never rebuilt to its former glory.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] A more modern, post-war building designed by Sybold van Ravesteyn was erected in 1951.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] The remaining parts of the second building were incorporated, while the third station's canopy remains to this day.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] 's-Hertogenbosch was again rebuilt in 1998, with an extension of the roof to the other island platform.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] Much of the renovation consisted of an aerial walkway, the Stationspasserelle, connecting the roadways on either side of the tracks, and the removal of a special ramp to the platforms.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] The station is an important interchange station, with trains coming from several different directions.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] 's-Hertogenbosch was the only Dutch station which provided in Auto-Train services.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] Services ran into Avignon, Bologna and Livorno.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] Auto-Trains were operated by Euro-Express-Traincharter.
[src:amsterdam-airport-schiphol/s-hertogenbosch-railway-station] There are 13 city bus lines, which are all operated by Arriva.
